04250nam a22006375i 9781575066288DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750662887 a10.1515/97815750662882doi  a(DE-B1597)584574  a(OCoLC)1269268640  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBL 7aHIS0020002bisacsh1 aConklin, Blane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOath Formulas in Biblical Hebrew /cBlane Conklin. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistic Studies in Ancient West Semitic ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Authenticating Element -- t3. Conditionally Formulated Oaths -- t4. Oaths Marked with ky -- t5. Exceptions and Objections -- t6. Conclusions -- t7. Appendix: Oath Formulas in Other Semitic Languages -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe eponymous protagonist of the biblical story of Ruth, a Moabite widow, is so desperate to follow her widowed mother-in-law back to Israel that she swears an oath. Regardless of the translation one may choose, the sense is the same: Ruth promises to stick by Naomi's side for at least as long as they both shall live. Ruth's intention with respect to the two widows' proximity once they cross the final river is not so unanimous in the translations, however. According to the NRSV, Ruth says:(1) "May the Lord do thus and so to me, and more as well, if even death parts me from you!"The njpsv is representative of many other translations with its rendering:(2) "Thus and more may the Lord do to me if anything but death parts me from you."The difference may seem trivial, but the contradiction between the italicized phrases is total. Either death will not ultimately separate them, or it will, in Ruth's view. The issue here is not a theological one, nor is this an archaeological issue. Rather, the issue is of a linguistic nature. What does the Hebrew phrase mean?The solution to the problem is fairly straightforward. The first step is to recognize that Ruth's statement is an oath. Oaths often employ formulaic, elliptical phrases. Therefore, it is necessary to gather together in one place as many of these formulas as possible so that the patterns, tendencies, and divergences may be seen within a larger matrix. Conklin's study intriguingly compiles precisely these phrases and formulas in order to solve the mystery of interpreting Biblical Hebrew oath formulas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066288zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575066288/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK